          strand: 'Frame',
          description:
            'Human-Centred Design is an approach to engineering design that prioritizes the lived experience of the stakeholders. It ensures the engineering solution is technically and socially sound and validly addresses the opportunity. To implement, the human perspective should be involved in every step of the design process [1]. It often takes the form of a cyclical 5-step process: empathize, define, ideate, prototype, test & iterate [2], but may vary in different implementations. Overall it ensures a need is defined that addresses actual human struggles, rather than just technical inefficiencies.',
          howUsed:
            'We primarily used this while developing our need to reframe the opportunity, but tried to implement it throughout the entire process. To empathize, we met with the community and analyzed previous interviews the design team had. We tried to uncover the true needs of the staff and the children beyond what was presented in the received RFP. We also tried to recall our experiences working with children aged 2.5–12 and emulate their perspective. To define, we used our understanding of their lived experience to rescope and re-frame the need and opportunity with a more human-oriented approach. We prioritized the community, child autonomy, as well as overall speed and simplicity instead of the wristband itself. When we generated ideas and requirements, we focused on amplifying this framing so that design solutions would be forced to prioritize it. However, we struggled to fully integrate this into our testing as described in the critical reflection of Proxy Tests.',
          evidence: '/*What evidence do you have?*/',
          assessment:
            'This CTMF was introduced briefly in ESC102 Lecture 10 [3], but most discussion surrounded a similar Design for Social Justice CTMF. Despite its small place in official content, I feel like it serves as a central theme of Praxis II. Working with external communities and potentially vulnerable stakeholders led the course to place more emphasis on the idea of Human Centred designs. I dedicated time to research it independently and already found many links to it in my approach to engineering design. I believe it has significant value in the framing strand of design. Choosing to put people at the centre of designs may be tedious, adding length and complexity to the process, but I see its worth as it ensures the end product has the intended effect on humanity.\n\nI think this is most useful during early design. Developing opportunities and requirements with this lens will ensure that it has residual effects in the rest of the process. However, in order to be used properly, it should be consistently integrated throughout the entire design process. If implemented consistently, human-centred designs would undoubtedly be more beneficial. It forces the design team to confront the various unknowns early and opens a line of consistent communication between them and the stakeholders. However, this communication can slow design iterations down and extend projects, straining time and resources of those involved. If that communication is not properly established, teams may be tempted to assume the perspective of stakeholders based on previous experiences. This means gaps may not truly be fulfilled for this specific project. The understanding of the opportunity and design must be continuously revisited and communicated between parties.\n\nI largely link this to my dedication to volunteerism. I consider myself selfless and often am dedicating time and energy to help others. I am very involved with the Rotary International organization, of which I mention for its slogan that I resonate with: Service Above Self. I want to use Human Centred Design to expand my dedication to this idea and put the stakeholders above my personal interests. Though I must be confident in my knowledge and abilities, I want to ensure that they are the ones whose needs are prioritized in the process. This primarily manifested in my advocacy for child autonomy and recognition of their perspective throughout the project. It also creates a more sustainable design as the solution will better fit into the current lived experience of the community, making implementation easier and long-standing.',
          images: [],
          citations: [
            { label: '1', citation: 'Wikipedia Contributors, "Human-centered design," Wikipedia, Jan. 31, 2019. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human-centered_design', url: 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human-centered_design' },
            { label: '2', citation: 'C. Ukagwu and S. Gray, "Applying the principles of Design Thinking to the Intensive Care Environment," University of Toronto Medical Journal, vol. 100, no. 1, Feb. 2023, doi: https://doi.org/10.33137/utmj.v100i1.40352.', url: 'https://doi.org/10.33137/utmj.v100i1.40352' },
            { label: '3', citation: 'Praxis II 2026 Teaching Team, "ESC102 2026 10," ESC102: Praxis II, Dept. of Engineering Science, University of Toronto, Toronto, ON, Jan. 2026.', url: '/files/projects/praxis2/ESC102 2026 10.pdf' },
          ],
