          id: 'civ102-ctmf2',
          name: 'TRIZ',
          strand: 'Converge',
          description:
            'TRIZ (Theory of Inventive Problem Solving) is a tool used to solve problems by identifying and resolving technical contradictions [1]. A technical contradiction occurs when improving one parameter of a system causes another parameter to deteriorate. Rather than accepting a compromise or a "middle ground" solution, TRIZ uses a system of 40 Inventive Principles and a Contradiction Matrix to find solutions that improve both parameters simultaneously.',
          howUsed:
            'We hadn\'t covered TRIZ during the bridge project, so we couldn\'t use it as a tool. However, it would have had significant value if implemented in our process. We faced many contradictions when trying to optimize the bridge, balancing weight and strength. We developed the pi-beam with girders which after testing proved to be not very successful. Using TRIZ, we would have identified the contradiction between Strength (Parameter 14) and Weight of Moving Object (Parameter 1). Looking at the Contradiction Matrix [2], one suggested principle is Principle 1: Segmentation. That includes dividing the object into independent parts, making it easy to disassemble, and increasing the degree of fragmentation — none of which would be implementable in the bridge. Solutions of Principle 8: Anti-weight, and Principle 40: Composite materials would violate the restrictions of the assignment. But Principle 15: Dynamics suggests allowing a characteristic to change, or making it movable/adaptable. As CIV102 is primarily a statics course, we haven\'t even considered a design that would allow movement to a safe capacity. We could have had an entirely new approach to the bridge. When testing, we noticed the bridges that were able to bounce and adapt to the train\'s load purposely managed to carry some of the highest loads in the cohort.',
          evidence:
            'See the TRIZ contradiction matrix results and the inventive principles reference.',
          assessment:
            'This tool is most useful when feeling stuck and having to make a compromise. It provides a structured way to move past seemingly incompatible features and toward a justified, inventive solution. By breaking a problem down into standard parameters, it removes personal biases and forces you to look at objective patterns of innovation. It tries to turn a trade-off into a betterment for multiple components. In the bridge project, we settled for a compromise because we didn\'t have a framework to help us think outside that box and make a lightweight and strong bridge.\n\nI think the biggest benefit of TRIZ is how it pushes you to consider solutions that seem counter-intuitive at first. For instance, dynamics would have completely changed our approach to the bridge\'s structural integrity by moving away from statics. However, this isn\'t a guaranteed solution to the problem. It is an idea generation to help converge and iterate. There may be a lot more work to be done to make one of these principles compatible with the current design, changing it drastically. It should be used early in the process to prevent delays from feeling stuck and potential complete redesigns.\n\nI see a lot of value in TRIZ for my work because it challenges the idea that engineering has to be about making sacrifices. It aligns with my appreciation of simplicity because it encourages finding solutions to the root of a problem, rather than accepting a trade off. Even though we didn\'t use it for the bridge, analyzing our compromises through this lens makes me realize that there is almost always a way to innovate out of a contradiction with the right tools.',
